  "text": "The backscattered signal from the nodes can be generally described as an infinite train of random symbols with a binary ASK or binary PSK modulation. The simple binary-switch modulator initially shown in Fig. 1 produces unshaped rectangular symbols due to the near-instantaneous switching of the antenna between two load impedances. Fourier analysis of these signals [19] yields a closed-form derivation of the spectrum [CITATION_1] where is the pulse amplitude and is the symbol duration. Approximately 90% of the signal energy is concentrated in the range around the node's subcarrier frequency. The amount of upper sideband energy in the range of (or equivalently in the lower sideband ) is only 2.5%, or 16 dB relative to the in-band energy. In the case of two neighboring nodes, separated exactly by the range bound and transmitting at the same rate, the adjacent channel energy in the nearest neighbor's channel is suppressed by the same 16 dB.",
